coexistence of Christians and muslims in Lebanon. It considers coexistence as a historically and geographically specific arrangement and organising principle of a distinctly secular form of life. On the basis of ethnographic and archival field research in Lebanon, Raja Abillama shows that Lebanese law and civil, criminal and religious (shari’a and ecclesiastical) judicial processes converge to secure a place for muslims and Christians to articulate their legally intelligible religious difference and distinctiveness, to secure the religious in place, and to contain what cannot be made legally intelligible – namely, their religious passions. This book’s holistic account of the interplay of law and religion in Lebanon is a contribution to debates surrounding sectarianism and secularism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslam. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianity. 0aReligion and lawzLebanon. 0aSecularismzLebanon. 4aIMES. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023z9783111318820oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079764040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978139950756140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781399507561423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781399507561/original  a978-3-11-079764-0  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b20